        "excerpt": "Now about that time Herod the king laid hands on some who belonged to the church in order to mistreat them. And he had James the brother of John put to death with a sword.",
        "body": "Luke opens the chapter with a deliberate verbal image: Herod *laid hands on* (*epiballō tas cheiras*) the church to harm it (12:1). The same phrase will recur in 12:11 when Peter testifies that the Lord rescued him from *the hand* of Herod. The chapter is a contest of hands — the king's hand reaches for the church; the Lord's hand reaches into the prison. Verse 1 sets the terms.\n\nThe Herod here is Agrippa I, grandson of Herod the Great, raised in Rome alongside the future emperor Claudius, granted rule over all of Palestine in AD 41. Unlike his grandfather, Agrippa cultivated Jewish religious sentiment — observing Torah publicly, championing the Sanhedrin. The execution of James the son of Zebedee by the sword (12:2) is not random brutality; it is a calculated gesture to please the Jerusalem leadership. James is the first apostle martyred, fulfilling Jesus's prophecy in Mark 10:38-39 that he and his brother would drink the cup the Lord drank. Luke records the martyrdom in a single sentence — no dying speech, no mourning scene — and moves on. The understatement is deliberate: not every faithful death gets a Stephen-like narrative (Acts 7). Some are dispatched in a line.\n\nVerse 3 names Herod's motive without sentiment: *when he saw that it pleased the Jews*. Persecution here is opinion-poll-driven. He moves on Peter because the killing of James polled well. Peter is arrested during Unleavened Bread; execution is deferred until after Passover, presumably to avoid contaminating the festival. The political calculation is precise; the theological framing is corrupt — Herod uses Passover as a political schedule, while Luke is about to show the reader what Passover actually means.\n\nVerse 5 is the chapter's first great hinge. *So Peter was kept in the prison, but prayer for him was being made fervently by the church to God.* The Greek *ektenōs* means 'stretched-out, intense' — the same root used of athletes straining. The verb is imperfect: *was being made* continuously. The church does not have political leverage, no friendly governor, no Roman citizen-status play. It has prayer, and it uses it without ceasing.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Ektenōs* (fervently, 12:5) appears only three times in the NT (Luke 22:44 — Jesus in Gethsemane; 1 Peter 4:8; here). The vocabulary is Luke's own quiet cross-reference: the church prays as Jesus prayed in His own night of arrest. *Epiballō tas cheiras* (laid hands on, 12:1) is a Septuagintal idiom for hostile seizure (cf. Genesis 22:12; Esther 6:2). Luke's diction is dense from the first verse."
