        "number": 5,
        "title": "The word kept growing — and the mission resumed",
        "range": "12:24-25",
        "excerpt": "But the word of the Lord continued to grow and to be multiplied. And Barnabas and Saul returned from Jerusalem when they had fulfilled their mission, taking along with them John, who was also called Mark.",
        "body": "Verse 24 is one of Luke's signature progress-reports (cf. 6:7; 9:31; 16:5; 19:20; 28:30-31). After the chapter's relentless drama — apostolic execution, royal persecution, supernatural rescue, dismissive church, divine judgment, decomposing king — Luke renders the verdict in a single sentence. The conjunction is *de* — 'but' or 'and yet.' Herod's body decays; the word grows. The verb pair *auxanō* (grow) and *plēthunō* (multiply) is taken from Genesis 1:28 — the creation mandate now fulfilled in the gospel's organic expansion. The word is treated as a living thing, irrepressible by political opposition.\n\nThis is Lukan theology of history in concentrated form. Luke does not argue that the church will prevail because of its own resources, faithfulness, or strategic skill. The church in this very chapter has had an apostle killed, lost Peter to 'another place,' misunderstood its own answered prayer, and remained vulnerable to imperial overreach. None of that has stopped the word. The word does what it does because of the One whose word it is. Earthly kingdoms rise and decay; the kingdom of the word grows.\n\nVerse 25 is Luke's transition into the second half of Acts. Barnabas and Saul return from Jerusalem (the famine-relief mission begun in 11:29-30), bringing John Mark with them. The mention of Mark is forward-looking: he will accompany the first missionary journey (13:5), defect at Perga (13:13), and become the cause of the Paul-Barnabas separation (15:36-41) — but he will also eventually be restored (2 Timothy 4:11) and write the Gospel that bears his name. Luke quietly plants the seed of all that future development in a single closing verse.\n\nThe chapter that began with Herod laying hands on the church to harm it (12:1) ends with Barnabas and Saul laying hands on John Mark to extend it. The hostile *hand* of verse 1 has been answered by the missional *taking* of verse 25. Between them lie a martyrdom, a deliverance, a death, and a still-multiplying word. This is the structure on which Luke ends Acts 12 and on which he will build the rest of the book.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Auxanō* (12:24) is the verb used of plants growing (Matthew 6:28; Mark 4:8) and of John the Baptist growing strong in spirit (Luke 1:80). Combined with *plēthunō* (multiply, from the same root as *plēthos*, 'multitude'), it is the language of Genesis 1:22, 28; 9:1. Luke is making a creation-theology claim: the gospel is the new creation's growth. *Sumparalambanō* (taking along with them, 12:25) is the technical term for choosing a missionary partner (cf. 15:37-38). The new missionary configuration is in place by the chapter's last word."
